
Imports are resolved before AST body semantics.
AST consumes a file-local visibility environment through `ScopeContext`.
It may validate semantic use of visible symbols, but it must not rebuild import bindings or rediscover top-level visibility.

## Main owners

- Stage 0 discovers source-backed packages, builder-supported source assets and provider-backed external files.
- Header import preparation resolves import paths, aliases, module-root exports, namespace records, source-backed package surfaces, binding-backed package symbols, prelude/builtin names, receiver-method visibility and collision rules.
- Dependency sorting uses header-provided dependency edges.
- AST uses `ScopeContext` to resolve expressions and type references through the active visibility maps.
- HIR carries stable external IDs only.
- Backends map those IDs to helpers, imports, glue, runtime names or target-native operations.

No stage after header import preparation should rebuild import visibility from raw source syntax.

## Source-backed packages and module public surfaces

Source-backed packages are normal modules with one unique non-config `#*.bst` root.
They participate in module-level dependency sorting.

The root filename is cosmetic. Its strict `export:` block is the API boundary.
Public authored declarations, grouped re-exports, exported constants and exported type surfaces still need to be ordered before outside declarations that import them through the module boundary.

Ordinary root imports and declarations outside `export:` remain private to the root file.
Grouped public re-exports define the public API name.

Module public API maps are built from:

- public authored headers inside the root's `export:` block
- grouped imports inside `export:`
- grouped aliases inside those imports

Legacy inline `export`, bare namespace exports and wildcard exports are outside the current surface.

## Namespace records

Source namespace imports create shallow field-access-only import records.
Import records are not first-class values.
Import source child paths directly rather than walking source path segments through namespace fields.

External package namespace imports can expose recursive child namespace records for package-local symbol paths such as `io.input.*`.
That recursion belongs to virtual package metadata, not source module surfaces.

## Binding-backed packages

Binding-backed packages are virtual typed symbols implemented outside Beanstalk source. They resolve through `ExternalPackageRegistry` and expose opaque types, constants and free functions only.

External package membership uses:

- stable `ExternalPackageId` values
- readable package paths
- structured package-local symbol paths
- origin metadata
- stable frontend IDs such as `ExternalFunctionId`

All binding-backed packages, whether registered directly by a builder or produced by
an import provider, share one external-package identity model.
The prelude `io` namespace alias is a separate bare-name visibility policy for `@core/io`, not a package kind.

Binding-backed packages don't register source-style receiver methods.
Use a source-owned wrapper type when method-style ergonomics are wanted over an external handle.
The HTML `@html` package's `Canvas` wrapper is the shape to copy: the raw `@web/canvas` symbols stay binding-backed, while method-style calls come from an ordinary source-owned wrapper.

Project-local and Builder source-backed packages resolve through `SourcePackageRegistry`. Binding-backed Core, Builder and ProjectLocal packages resolve through `ExternalPackageRegistry`. Both registries carry `PackageMetadata`, but origin and backing don't alter import syntax or the strict module `export:` boundary.

## External import providers

External import providers live under `BuilderSurface` and resolve non-Beanstalk import sources into typed package/type/function IDs before AST consumes visibility.

Grouped imports for virtual external packages resolve through external package metadata before source module-boundary enforcement.
Source imports still go through module public-surface checks before source target resolution, so virtual package lookup doesn't weaken source-backed package or module privacy.

Provider-backed external JavaScript is the main current example.
The frontend registers typed package metadata.
The backend later emits only the runtime assets and glue reachable from the compiled bundle.

## Source file kinds

Builder-supported source file kinds resolve through the same extensionless source import path as `.bst` files when the active builder declares support.

HTML supports:

- Beandown `.bd`
- plain Markdown `.md`

Both become private synthetic `content #String` constants during header preparation.
Recognised but unsupported source kinds are rejected with typed import diagnostics.

There is no source-kind-specific AST, HIR or borrow-checker path.
This keeps content assets integrated without making every asset format a compiler sublanguage.

## Receiver methods and visibility

Header import preparation doesn't import source-authored receiver methods as independent symbols.

A source-authored receiver method belongs to the same file as its nominal receiver type.
It becomes callable wherever the receiver type is visible.
Namespace imports may make the receiver type visible, but methods are not namespace fields and can't be grouped-imported or aliased independently.

External packages don't expose receiver methods.
Compiler-owned collection and map operations are builtin member access, not user extension methods.

## Collision policy

All user-visible names go through one collision policy.
Same-file declarations, source imports, external imports, type aliases, prelude symbols and builtins can't silently shadow each other.

Aliases have two different rules depending on where they appear:

- Ordinary import aliases are file-local. They can't be independently re-exported.
- An alias authored inside a grouped import in `export:` defines the public API name for that exported symbol.

Both kinds must not collide with visible names. Leading-case mismatches warn.

Ordinary examples:

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    import @some/path { Symbol as LocalName }
    import @core/io { io as CoreIo }
]

Module export alias example:

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    export:
        import @some/path { Symbol as PublicName }
    ;
]

The grouped alias inside `export:` is the public API name. It isn't a file-local-only alias that happens to be exported.

## Related reading

- @../stages/header-parsing (Stage 2: Header parsing): where imports, aliases and module exports are parsed
- @../stages/dependency-sorting (Stage 3: Dependency sorting): how source-backed package root surfaces participate in ordering
- @../stages/ast-construction (Stage 4: AST construction): `ScopeContext` visibility consumption
- @../backend/external-js-and-runtime-assets (External JavaScript and runtime assets): provider-backed JS and runtime asset planning

If a lookup path needs to behave differently for source imports, module-boundary imports and external packages, put that distinction in the visibility/import layer.
Don't hide it in expression resolution.

## HIR handoff

HIR stores stable external IDs, not package syntax or backend runtime names.

Borrow validation can resolve external IDs through the external package registry to recover access rules and return-alias metadata.
Backends map the same IDs to target-specific helpers, imports, generated glue, runtime names or target-native operations.

That lets frontend semantics stay target-neutral while backends still own runtime integration.
